    <item>
      <title>Authority Model</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/governance/authority-model/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/governance/authority-model/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;authority-model&#34;&gt;Authority Model&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Authority within PlainSight Lab is defined, bounded, and attributable.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Authority does not arise from personality, reputation, expertise, or influence.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;Authority arises only from constitutional definition and documented role.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;If authority is not explicitly granted, it does not exist.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;authority-types&#34;&gt;Authority Types&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;PlainSight Lab recognizes three authority types:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;1-epistemic-authority&#34;&gt;1. Epistemic Authority&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The authority to define canonical truth.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This includes:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Specification definition&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Invariant articulation&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Problem classification&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Formal correction criteria&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Epistemic authority is constrained by the Constitution and subject to amendment thresholds.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
